## First principles

The generative rules the rest of this file's conventions fall out of live
in [`PRINCIPLES.md`](PRINCIPLES.md). When a decision isn't covered by a
specific convention below, reason from there.

## Secrets

- Credentials live in `~/.key/` (or wherever `keyvault/` is pointed at).
  Read them from there at point of use — never hardcode a secret value or
  echo one into a transcript or commit.
- `~/.key/` starts locked after every reboot on the platforms that support
  encryption-at-rest (`keyvault/README.md`); `_lib/secrets.py` fails with a
  clear locked message rather than silently proceeding, and the freshness
  check flags any job that stalled because of it.

## Git

- Set your account/identity convention here once you have one — which
  account owns these repos, whether they're private, HTTPS vs SSH.
- Commit with explicit identity if the default `git config` on this
  machine isn't yours: `git -c user.name='<you>' -c user.email='<you>'
  commit ...`

## Python

- System/scheduled scripts: the bare system `python3` (no venv) — this is
  why `_lib/` stays stdlib-only; `_lib/selftest.py` enforces it.
- Project tools with real dependencies: give the project its own venv.

## Scheduling

- Job source of truth: `scheduler/manifest.yml`; apply with
  `scheduler/sync.sh` (crontab on Linux, launchd on macOS). Never hand-edit
  crontab or a `.plist` directly — `sync.sh --check` will flag the drift,
  never silently fix it.
- See `scheduler/CONVENTIONS.md` for the found-work-vs-breakage exit
  convention and why jobs must self-notify (neither scheduler pages you by
  default).

## Machine fleet (if you run more than one host)

- Name this host here once you have a naming convention. If you run
  several machines, a short shared protocol doc (which host owns which
  capability, where state/heartbeats live) pays off fast — don't build it
  until you actually have a second host.
- One home per capability: don't let the same job run scheduled on two
  hosts "just in case" — pick one, note it here.

